# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: antiknock-agent
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] Historically, 1,2-dibromoethane was used as a component in anti-knock additives in leaded fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] It reacts with lead residues to generate volatile lead bromides, thereby preventing fouling of the engine with lead deposits.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] It has been used as a pesticide in soil and on various crops.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] The applications were initiated after the forced retirement of 1,2-dibromo-3-chloropropane (DBCP).
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] Most of these uses have been stopped in the U.S.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] It continues to be used as a fumigant for treatment of logs for termites and beetles, and for control of moths in beehives.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane has wider applications in the preparation of other organic compounds including those carrying modified diazocine rings and vinyl bromide that is a precursor to some fire retardants.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] In organic synthesis, 1,2-dibromoethane is used to brominate carbanions and to activate magnesium for certain Grignard reagents.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] In the latter process, 1,2-dibromoethane reacts with magnesium, producing ethylene and magnesium bromide, which are innocuous, exposing a more active portion of the magnesium particle to the substrate.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane causes changes in the metabolism and severe destruction of living tissues.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] The known empirical LD50 values for 1,2-dibromoethane are 140 mg kg−1 (oral, rat), and 300.0 mg kg−1 (dermal, rabbit).
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is a known carcinogen, with pre-1977 exposure levels ranking it as the most carcinogenic substance on the HERP Index.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] The effects on people of breathing high levels are not known, but animal studies with short-term exposures to high levels caused depression and collapse, indicating effects on the brain.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] Changes in the brain and behavior were also seen in young rats whose male parents had breathed 1,2-dibromoethane, and birth defects were observed in the young of animals that were exposed while pregnant.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] 1,2-Dibromoethane is not known to cause birth defects in humans.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dibromoethane] Swallowing has caused death at 40ml doses.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] The chemical compound **1,2-dichloroethane**, commonly known as **ethylene dichloride** (**EDC**), is a chlorinated hydrocarbon.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] It is a colourless liquid with a chloroform-like odour.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] The most common use of 1,2-dichloroethane is in the production of vinyl chloride, which is used to make polyvinyl chloride (PVC) pipes, furniture and automobile upholstery, wall coverings, housewares, and automobile parts.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane is also used generally as an intermediate for other organic chemical compounds, and as a solvent.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] It forms azeotropes with many other solvents, including water (at a boiling point of 70.5 °C or 158.9 °F or 343.6 K) and other chlorocarbons.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Although the *Gezelschap* in practice did not do much in-depth scientific research, they and their publications were highly regarded.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Part of that acknowledgement is that 1,2-dichloroethane was called "Dutch oil" in old chemistry.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] This is also the origin of the archaic term "olefiant gas" (oil-making gas) for ethylene, for in this reaction it is ethylene that makes the Dutch oil.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] "Olefiant gas" is the etymological origin of the modern term "olefins", the family of hydrocarbons of which ethylene is the first member.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Nearly 20 million tons of 1,2-dichloroethane are produced annually in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Approximately 95% of the world's production of 1,2-dichloroethane is used in the production of vinyl chloride monomer (VCM) with hydrogen chloride as a byproduct.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] VCM is the precursor to polyvinyl chloride.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] The hydrogen chloride can be re-used in the production of more 1,2-dichloroethane via the oxychlorination route described above.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] 1,2-Dichloroethane has been used as degreaser and paint remover but this use has phased out due to its toxicity.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] As a useful 'building block' reagent, it is used as an intermediate in the production of diverse organic compounds such as ethylenediamine and higher ethyleneamines.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] In the laboratory it is occasionally used as a source of chlorine, with elimination of ethene and chloride.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Via several steps, 1,2-dichloroethane is a precursor to 1,1,1-trichloroethane.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Historically, before leaded petrol was phased out, chloroethanes were used as an additive in petrol to prevent lead buildup in engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] It is also toxic (especially by inhalation due to its high vapour pressure) and possibly carcinogenic.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Its high solubility and 50-year half-life in anoxic aquifers make it a perennial pollutant and health risk that is very expensive to treat conventionally, requiring a method of bioremediation.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] While the chemical is not used in consumer products manufactured in the U.S., a case was reported in 2009 of molded plastic consumer products (toys and holiday decorations) from China that released 1,2-dichloroethane into homes at levels high enough to produce cancer risk.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Substitutes are recommended and will vary according to application.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Dioxolane and toluene are possible substitutes as solvents.
[src:antiknock-agent/1-2-dichloroethane] Dichloroethane is unstable in the presence of aluminium and, when moist, with zinc and iron.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Various alcohols are used as fuel for internal combustion engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The first four aliphatic alcohols (methanol, ethanol, propanol, and butanol) are of interest as fuels because they can be synthesized chemically or biologically, and they have characteristics which allow them to be used in internal combustion engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The general chemical formula for alcohol fuel is **CnH2n+1OH**.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Most methanol is produced from natural gas, although it can be produced from biomass using very similar chemical processes.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Ethanol is commonly produced from biological material through fermentation processes.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Biobutanol has the advantage in combustion engines in that its energy density is closer to gasoline than the simpler alcohols (while still retaining over 25% higher octane rating); however, biobutanol is currently more difficult to produce than ethanol or methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] When obtained from biological materials and/or biological processes, they are known as **bioalcohols** (e.g.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] There is no chemical difference between biologically produced and chemically produced alcohols.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] One advantage shared by the four major alcohol fuels is their high octane rating.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol and ethanol can both be derived from fossil fuels, biomass, or from carbon dioxide and water.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Ethanol has most commonly been produced through fermentation of sugars, and methanol has most commonly been produced from synthesis gas, but there are more modern ways to obtain these fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Enzymes can be used instead of fermentation.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol is the simpler molecule, and ethanol can be made from methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol can be produced industrially from nearly any biomass, including animal waste, or from carbon dioxide and water or steam by first converting the biomass to synthesis gas in a gasifier.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] It can also be produced in a laboratory using electrolysis or enzymes.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] As a fuel, methanol and ethanol both have advantages and disadvantages over fuels such as petrol (gasoline) and diesel fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In spark ignition engines, both alcohols can run at much higher exhaust gas recirculation rates and with higher compression ratios.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Both alcohols have a high octane rating, with ethanol at 109 RON (Research Octane Number), 90 MON (Motor Octane Number), (which equates to 99.5 AKI) and methanol at 109 RON, 89 MON (which equates to 99 AKI).
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Note that AKI refers to 'Anti-Knock Index' which averages the RON and MON ratings (RON+MON)/2, and is used on U.S. gas station pumps.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Ordinary European petrol is typically 95 RON, 85 MON, equal to 90 AKI.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] As a compression ignition engine fuel, both alcohols create very few particulates, but their low cetane number means that an ignition improver like glycol must be mixed into the fuel at approx.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] When used in spark ignition engines alcohols have the potential to reduce NOx, CO, HC and particulates.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] A test with E85 fueled Chevrolet Luminas showed that NMHC went down by 20-22%, NOx by 25-32% and CO by 12-24% compared to reformulated gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Toxic emissions of benzene and 1,3-butadiene also decreased while aldehyde emissions increased, acetaldehyde in particular.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Tailpipe emissions of CO2 also decrease due to the lower carbon-to-hydrogen ratio of these alcohols, and improved engine efficiency.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol and ethanol fuels contain soluble and insoluble contaminants.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Halide ions, which are soluble contaminants, such as chloride ions, have a large effect on the corrosivity of alcohol fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Halide ions increase corrosion in two ways: they chemically attack passivating oxide films on several metals causing pitting corrosion, and they increase the conductivity of the fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Increased electrical conductivity promotes electrical, galvanic and ordinary corrosion in the fuel system.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Soluble contaminants such as aluminum hydroxide, itself a product of corrosion by halide ions, clog the fuel system over time.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] To prevent corrosion the fuel system must be made of suitable materials, electrical wires must be properly insulated and the fuel level sensor must be of pulse and hold type magneto resistive or other similar non-contact type.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In addition, high quality alcohol should have a low concentration of contaminants and have a suitable corrosion inhibitor added.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Scientific evidence reveals that water is an inhibitor for corrosion by ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The experiments are done with E50, which is more aggressive and speeds up the corrosion effect.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] It is very clear that by increasing the amount of water in fuel ethanol one can reduce corrosion.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] At 2% or 20,000 ppm water in the ethanol fuel the corrosion stopped.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In line with the observations in Japan, hydrous ethanol is known to be less corrosive than anhydrous ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The reaction mechanism is 3 EtOH + Al -> Al(OEt)3 + 3⁄2 H2 at lower-mid blends.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] When enough water is present in the fuel, aluminum will react preferably with water to produce Al2O3, repairing the protective aluminum oxide layer.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The aluminum alkoxide does not make a tight oxide layer; water is essential to repair the holes in the oxide layer.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol and ethanol are incompatible with some polymers.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The alcohol reacts with the polymers causing swelling, and over time oxygen breaks down the carbon-carbon bonds in the polymer causing a reduction in tensile strength.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] For the past few decades though, most cars have been designed to tolerate up to 10% ethanol (E10) without problem.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This includes both fuel system compatibility and lambda compensation of fuel delivery with fuel injection engines featuring closed loop lambda control.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In some engines ethanol may degrade some compositions of plastic or rubber fuel delivery components designed for conventional petrol, and also be unable to lambda compensate the fuel properly.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] "FlexFuel" vehicles have upgraded fuel system and engine components which are designed for long life using E85 or M85, and the ECU can adapt to any fuel blend between gasoline and E85 or M85.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Typical upgrades include modifications to: fuel tanks, fuel tank electrical wiring, fuel pumps, fuel filters, fuel lines, filler tubes, fuel level sensors, fuel injectors, seals, fuel rails, fuel pressure regulators, valve seats and inlet valves.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] "Total Flex" autos destined for the Brazilian market can use E100 (100% ethanol).
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] One liter of ethanol releases 21.1 MJ in combustion, a liter of methanol 15.8 MJ and a liter of gasoline approximately 32.6 MJ.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In other words, for the same energy content as one liter or one gallon of gasoline, one needs 1.6 liters/gallons of ethanol and 2.1 liters/gallons of methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The raw energy-per-volume numbers produce misleading fuel consumption numbers, however, because alcohol-fueled engines can be made substantially more energy-efficient.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] A larger percentage of the energy released by combustion of a liter of alcohol fuel can be converted to useful work.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This difference in efficiency can partially or totally balance out the energy density difference, depending on the particular engines being compared.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol fuel has been proposed as a future biofuel, often as an alternative to the hydrogen economy.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol has a long history as a racing fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Early Grand Prix Racing used blended mixtures as well as pure methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The fuel was primarily used in North America after the war.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, methanol for racing purposes has largely been based on methanol produced from syngas derived from natural gas and therefore this methanol would not be considered a biofuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Methanol is a possible biofuel, however, when the syngas is derived from biomass.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In theory, methanol can also be produced from sustainably sourced biomass and ultimately carbon dioxide, and by hydrogen electrolysis using nuclear power, geothermal power or some other renewable energy source (see Carbon Recycling International).
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Compared to bioethanol, the primary advantage of methanol biofuel is its much greater well-to-wheel efficiency.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This is particularly relevant in temperate climates where fertilizers are needed to grow sugar or starch crops to make ethanol, whereas methanol can be produced from unfertilized lignocellulose (woody) biomass.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Ethanol is already being used extensively as a fuel additive, and the use of ethanol fuel alone or as part of a mix with gasoline is increasing.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Compared to methanol its primary advantage is that it is less corrosive and non-toxic, although the fuel will produce some toxic exhaust emissions.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Since 2007, IndyCar has used ethanol as its exclusive fuel, after 40 years of using methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Since September 2007 petrol stations in NSW, Australia have been mandated to supply all their petrol with 2% ethanol content.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Propanol and butanol are considerably less toxic and less volatile than methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In particular, butanol has a high flash point of 35 °C, which is a benefit for fire safety, but may be a difficulty for starting engines in cold weather.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The concept of flash point is, however, not directly applicable to engines as the compression of the air in the cylinder means that the temperature is several hundred degrees Celsius before ignition takes place.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This organism also dies when the butanol content of whatever it is fermenting rises to 2%.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] For comparison, yeast dies when the ethanol content of its feedstock hits 14%.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Specialized strains can tolerate even greater ethanol concentrations - so-called turbo yeast can withstand up to 16% ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, if ordinary Saccharomyces yeast can be modified to improve its ethanol resistance, scientists may yet one day produce a strain of the Weizmann organism with a butanol resistance higher than the natural boundary of 7%.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This would be useful because butanol has a higher combustion energy density than ethanol, and because waste fibre left over from sugar crops used to make ethanol could be made into butanol, raising the alcohol yield of fuel crops without requiring more crops to be planted.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Despite these drawbacks, DuPont and BP have recently announced that they are jointly to build a small scale butanol fuel demonstration plant alongside the large bioethanol plant they are jointly developing with Associated British Foods.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The company Energy Environment International developed a method for producing butanol from biomass, which involves the use of two separate micro-organisms in sequence to minimize production of acetone and ethanol byproducts.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The Swiss company Butalco GmbH uses a special technology to modify yeasts in order to produce butanol instead of ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Yeasts as production organisms for butanol have decisive advantages compared to bacteria.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The 3-carbon alcohol, propanol (C3H7OH), is not often used as a direct fuel source for petrol engines (unlike ethanol, methanol and butanol), with most being directed into use as a solvent.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, it is used as a source of hydrogen in some types of fuel cell; it can generate a higher voltage than methanol, which is the fuel of choice for most alcohol-based fuel cells.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, since propanol is harder to produce than methanol (biologically or from oil), methanol-utilizing fuel cells are preferred over those that utilize propanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Brazil was until recently the largest producer of alcohol fuel in the world, typically fermenting ethanol from sugarcane.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The country produces a total of 18 billion litres (4.8 billion gallons) annually, of which 3.5 billion liters are exported, 2 billion of them to the U.S.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Alcohol cars debuted in the Brazilian market in 1979 and became quite popular because of a heavy subsidy, but in the 1980s prices rose and gasoline regained the leading market share.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, from 2003 on, alcohol has rapidly increased its market share once again because of new technologies involving flexible-fuel engines, called "Flex" or "Total Flex" by all major car manufacturers (Volkswagen, General Motors, Fiat, etc.).
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] "Flex" engines work with gasoline, alcohol or any mixture of both fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] As of May 2009, more than 88% of new vehicles sold in Brazil are flex fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Because of the Brazilian leading production and technology, many countries became very interested in importing alcohol fuel and adopting the "Flex" vehicle concept.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] On March 7 of 2007, US president George W.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Bush visited the city of São Paulo to sign agreements with Brazilian president Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva on importing alcohol and its technology as an alternative fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] As early as 1935, China has made alcohol fuel powered cars.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] China has reported with a 70% methanol use to conventional gasoline an independence from crude oil.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The National Committee of Planning and Action Coordination for Clean Automobile had listed key technologies related to alcohol/ether fuel and accelerated industrialization in its main agenda.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Alcohol fuels had become part of five main alternative fuels, two of which were alcohols: methanol and ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The United States at the end of 2007 was producing 26.9 billion litres (7 billion gallons) per year.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] E10 or Gasohol is commonly marketed in Delaware and E85 is found in many states, particularly in the Midwest where ethanol from corn is produced locally.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Many states and municipalities have mandated that all gasoline fuel be blended with 10 percent alcohol (usually ethanol) during some or all of the year.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This is to reduce pollution and allows these areas to comply with federal pollution limits.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Because alcohol is partially oxygenated, it produces less overall pollution, including ozone.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] In some areas (California in particular) the regulations may also require other formulations or added chemicals that reduce pollution, but add complexity to the fuel distribution and increase the cost of the fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The first alcohol fuel in Japan began with **GAIAX** in 1999.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] GAIAX was developed in South Korea, and imported by Japan.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Because GAIAX was not gasoline, it was a tax-free object of the gas tax of Japan.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, as a result, the use of GAIAX came to be considered an act of smuggling in Japan by the government and the petroleum industry.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Retailing of GAIAX was done to avoid the tax evasion criticism by independently paying the diesel fuel tax in the legal system regulations.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Accidental vehicle fires where GAIAX was being refueled began to be reported in around 2000 when the tax evasion discussion had almost ended.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The car industry in Japan criticized GAIAX, saying that "fires broke out because high density alcohol had corroded the fuel pipes".
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] GAIAX was named a "high density alcohol fuel", and a campaign was executed to exclude it from the market long term.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Finally, the Ministry of Economy, Trade and Industry also joined this campaign.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The gasoline quality method was revised under the pretext of safety concerns in 2003.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This prohibited the manufacturing and sale of "High density alcohol fuel", and added a substantial GAIAX sales ban.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] By revising the law, fuel manufacturers are prohibited from adding 3% or more alcohol to gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] This revision to the law is grounds not to be able to sell alcohol fuel greater than E3 in Japan.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] The petroleum industry in Japan is now proceeding with research and development of an original alcohol fuel that differs from GAIAX.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] However, the commercial manufacture and sale of any new fuel may be barred by existing laws that currently exclude GAIAX from the market.
[src:antiknock-agent/alcohol-as-a-fuel] Moreover, the strong aversion by the Japanese consumer to a high density alcohol fuel of any type may prevent commercial success of any new fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The SN2 mechanism is not available for aryl substituents, where the trajectory to attack the carbon atom would be inside the ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Thus, only reactions catalyzed by organometallic catalysts are possible.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] C-alkylation is a process for the formation of carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The largest example of this takes place in the alkylation units of petrochemical plants, which convert low-molecular-weight alkenes into high octane gasoline components.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Electron-rich species such as phenols are also commonly alkylated to produce a variety of products; examples include linear alkylbenzenes used in the production of surfactants like LAS, or butylated phenols like BHT, which are used as antioxidants.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] This can be achieved using either acid catalysts like Amberlyst, or Lewis acids like aluminium.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] On a laboratory scale the Friedel–Crafts reaction uses alkyl halides, as these are often easier to handle than their corresponding alkenes, which tend to be gasses.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The reaction is catalysed by aluminium trichloride.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] This approach is rarely used industrially as alkyl halides are more expensive than alkenes.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The rate of alkylation follows the order tertiary amine < secondary amine < primary amine.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Typical alkylating agents are alkyl halides.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Industry often relies on green chemistry methods involving alkylation of amines with alcohols, the byproduct being water.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Hydroamination is another green method for N-alkylation.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] In the Menshutkin reaction, a tertiary amine is converted into a quaternary ammonium salt by reaction with an alkyl halide.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Similar reactions occur when tertiary phosphines are treated with alkyl halides, the products being phosphonium salts.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Thiols are readily alkylated to give thioethers via the thiol-ene reaction.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The reaction is typically conducted in the presence of a base or using the conjugate base of the thiol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Thioethers undergo alkylation to give sulfonium ions.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] When the alkylating agent is an alkyl halide, the conversion is called the Williamson ether synthesis.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alcohols are also good alkylating agents in the presence of suitable acid catalysts.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] For example, most methyl amines are prepared by alkylation of ammonia with methanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The alkylation of phenols is particularly straightforward since it is subject to fewer competing reactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] More complex alkylation of a alcohols and phenols involve ethoxylation.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Ethylene oxide is the alkylating group in this reaction.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] In the process called oxidative addition, low-valent metals often react with alkylating agents to give metal alkyls.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] This reaction is one step in the Cativa process for the synthesis of acetic acid from methyl iodide.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Many cross coupling reactions proceed via oxidative addition as well.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Electrophilic alkylating agents deliver the equivalent of an alkyl cation.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkyl halides are typical alkylating agents.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Trimethyloxonium tetrafluoroborate and triethyloxonium tetrafluoroborate are particularly strong electrophiles due to their overt positive charge and an inert leaving group (dimethyl or diethyl ether).
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Dimethyl sulfate is intermediate in electrophilicity.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Diazomethane is a popular methylating agent in the laboratory, but it is too hazardous (explosive gas with a high acute toxicity) to be employed on an industrial scale without special precautions.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Use of diazomethane has been significantly reduced by the introduction of the safer and equivalent reagent trimethylsilyldiazomethane.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Electrophilic, soluble alkylating agents are often toxic and carcinogenic, due to their tendency to alkylate DNA.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] This mechanism of toxicity is relevant to the function of anti-cancer drugs in the form of alkylating antineoplastic agents.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Some chemical weapons such as mustard gas (sulfide of dichloroethyl) function as alkylating agents.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkylated DNA either does not coil or uncoil properly, or cannot be processed by information-decoding enzymes.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Without functional DNA, the functioning of the cell ceases, leading to cell death.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Thus, these alkylating agents are cytotoxic.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Electrophilic alkylation uses Lewis acids and Brønsted acids, sometimes both.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Classically, Lewis acids, e.g., aluminium trichloride, are employed when the alkyl halide are used.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Brønsted acids are used when alkylating with olefins.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Typical catalysts are zeolites, i.e. solid acid catalysts, and sulfuric acid.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkylation in biology causes DNA damage.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] It is the transfer of alkyl groups to the nitrogenous bases.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] It is caused by alkylating agents such as EMS (Ethyl methanesulfonate).
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Bifunctional alkyl groups which have two alkyl groups in them cause cross linking in DNA.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkylation damaged ring nitrogen bases are repaired via the base excision repair (BER) pathway.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Several commodity chemicals are produced by alkylation.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Included are several fundamental benzene-based feedstocks such as ethylbenzene (precursor to styrene), cumene (precursor to phenol and acetone), linear alkylbenzene sulfonates (for detergents).
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] In a conventional oil refinery, isobutane is alkylated with low-molecular-weight alkenes (primarily a mixture of propene and butene) in the presence of a Brønsted acid catalyst, which can include solid acids (zeolites).
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The catalyst protonates the alkenes (propene, butene) to produce carbocations, which alkylate isobutane.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The product, called "alkylate", is composed of a mixture of high-octane, branched-chain paraffinic hydrocarbons (mostly isoheptane and isooctane).
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkylate is a premium gasoline blending stock because it has exceptional antiknock properties and is clean burning.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Alkylate is also a key component of avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] By combining fluid catalytic cracking, polymerization, and alkylation, refineries can obtain a gasoline yield of 70 percent.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] The widespread use of sulfuric acid and hydrofluoric acid in refineries poses significant environmental risks.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Ionic liquids are used in place of the older generation of strong Bronsted acids.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Complementing alkylation reactions are the reverse, dealkylations.
[src:antiknock-agent/alkylation] Prevalent are demethylations, which are prevalent in biology, organic synthesis, and other areas, especially for methyl ethers and methyl amines.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] An **antiknock agent** (or **knock inhibitor**) is a gasoline additive used to reduce engine knocking and increase the fuel's octane rating by raising the temperature and pressure at which auto-ignition occurs.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The mixture known as gasoline or petrol, when used in high compression internal combustion engines, has a tendency to knock (also called "pinging" or "pinking") and/or to ignite early before the correctly timed spark occurs (*pre-ignition*, refer to engine knocking).
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Notable early antiknock agents, especially tetraethyllead, added to gasoline included large amounts of toxic lead.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Some other chemicals used as gasoline additives are thought to be less toxic.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In Europe, after the earlier ban of lead antiknock additives, an effective ban of other metal-contained additives (MFA, metallic fuel additives) was established in 2004 with a specific limit for methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT) of 6 mg/l from 2011, lowered to 2 mg/l in 2014.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In recent years no use of MMT has been reported in the annual monitoring reports under the European fuel quality directive.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] By the end of the 1990s, North American refineries also voluntary stopped the use of MMT in petrol, since less contested antiknock additives and compounds, such as MTBE and ethanol, were available.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Gibson and Harry Ricardo in England and Thomas Midgley Jr. and Thomas Boyd in the United States.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The discovery that lead additives modified this behavior led to the widespread adoption of the practice in the 1920s and therefore more powerful higher compression engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The most popular additive was tetraethyllead.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] However, with the discovery of the environmental and health damage caused by the lead, attributed to Derek Bryce-Smith and Clair Cameron Patterson, and the incompatibility of lead with catalytic converters found on virtually all US automobiles since 1975, this practice began to wane in the 1980s.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Most countries are phasing out leaded fuel although different additives still contain lead compounds.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Other additives include aromatic hydrocarbons, ethers and alcohol (usually ethanol or methanol).
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In the U.S., where tetraethyllead had been blended with gasoline (primarily to boost octane levels) since the early 1920s, standards to phase out leaded gasoline were first implemented in 1973.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In 1995, leaded fuel accounted for only 0.6% of total gasoline sales and less than 2,000 tons of lead per year.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] From January 1, 1996, the Clean Air Act banned the sale of leaded fuel for use in on-road vehicles in the United States.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Possession and use of leaded gasoline in a regular on-road vehicle now carries a maximum US$10,000 fine in the United States.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] However, fuel containing lead may continue to be sold for off-road uses, including aircraft, racing cars, farm equipment, and marine engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The ban on leaded gasoline led to thousands fewer tons of lead being released into the air by automobiles.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Similar bans in other countries have resulted in sharply decreasing levels of lead in people's bloodstreams.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] A side effect of the lead additives was protection of the valve seats from erosion.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Many classic cars' engines have needed modification to use lead-free fuels since leaded fuels became unavailable.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] However, "lead substitute" products are also produced and can sometimes be found at auto parts stores.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Gasoline, as delivered at the pump, also contains additives to reduce internal engine carbon buildups, improve combustion, and to allow easier starting in cold climates.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In some parts of South America, Asia, and the Middle East, leaded gasoline is still in use.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Leaded gasoline was phased out in sub-Saharan Africa, starting 1 January 2006.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] A growing number of countries have drawn up plans to ban leaded gasoline in the near future.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Some experts speculate that leaded petrol was behind a global crime wave in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] To avoid deposits of lead inside the engine, lead scavengers are added to the gasoline together with tetraethyllead.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] As tetraethyllead use declined, industry had to decide how to make up the octane deficit between the principal marketable light fuels produced by their refineries, and the higher octane fuels needed for high-compression gasoline engines in the automobile fleet.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Around 70% of the difference was accommodated by more advanced processes at the refinery stage, cracking other hydrocarbon products from the distillation stack to modify them into fuels that would blend gasoline closer the appropriate octane.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Most of the rest of the octane deficit required chemical additives not derived from the refinery process.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Tetraethyl lead was largely replaced in the US with methyl tert-butyl ether starting in 1979.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] MTBE is a toxic water pollutant, and a series of groundwater contamination scandals starting in the 90's prompted the EPA to begin phasing MTBE out in 2000.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Ethanol has several issues as an antiknock additive.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] It is hydrophilic, pulling water vapor out of moist air, and it also increases the level of free oxygen in the fuel significantly.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Both of these cause significant degradation to traditionally constructed engines, posing both residue and corrosion issues in increasing proportion with increasing fractions of ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Whereas age-degraded gasoline may simply polymerize, evaporate, and thus lose its flammability, age-degraded gasoline-ethanol blends can cause severe damage if allowed to sit in an engine.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Automotive engines addressed this with the mandated shift over to ethanol-tolerant metals and seals, and with the use of smart electronic fuel injection, which has some flexibility to adjust combustion properties and timing.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Automotive engines did not see major issues because of these factors, and because automobiles in active use typically cycle through their gas tank in a matter of weeks.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In small carburetor engines, like generators and lawnmowers, ethanol damage became the dominant mode of failure.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT) has been used for many years in Canada and recently in Australia to boost octane ratings.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] It also allows old cars, designed to use leaded fuel, to run on unleaded fuel without the need for additives to prevent valve seat erosion.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] A large Canadian study from 2002 (funded by automakers, who are against its use) concluded that MMT impairs the effectiveness of automobile emission controls and increases pollution from motor vehicles.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Many studies have been undertaken over time that confirmed the use of MMT is compatible with vehicles and safe for human health and the environment.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In particular, a 2013 risk assessment on MMT was undertaken by ARCADIS Consulting, following a methodology developed by the European Commission.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] This risk assessment was verified by an independent panel and found by the EU Commission to be compliant with their methodology.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] MMT is manufactured by reduction of bis(methylcyclopentadienyl) manganese using triethylaluminium.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The reduction is conducted under an atmosphere of carbon monoxide.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] MMT is a so-called half-sandwich compound, or more specifically a piano-stool complex (since the three CO ligands are like the legs of a piano stool).
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The manganese atom in MMT is coordinated with three carbonyl groups as well as to the methylcyclopentadienyl ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] These hydrophobic organic ligands make MMT highly lipophilic, which may increase bioaccumulation.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] While the structure of MMT suggests lipophilicity and potential to bioaccumulate, comparison of bioconcentration factors (BCF) reported for plant and animal species in comparison to regulatory-based cutoffs (i.e., US EPA and EU REACH) indicates a low bioaccumulative potential of MMT.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Figures 2 and 3 of the study (pages 182 & 184) shows the BCF plotted against time and illustrates the potential BCF of MMT.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] From these figures, the upper curve (A) demonstrates the 9-day MMT BCF plateauing at approximately 400 in plants and 200 in fish, with both values well below the Bioaccumulative / Very Bioaccumulative (B/vB) thresholds of US EPA, EU REACH and Environment & Climate Change Canada.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] A variety of related complexes are known, including ferrocene, which is also under consideration as an additive to gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Ferrocene is the organometallic compound with the formula Fe(C5H5)2.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] It is the prototypical metallocene, a type of organometallic chemical compound consisting of two cyclopentadienyl rings bound on opposite sides of a central metal atom.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Such organometallic compounds are also known as sandwich compounds.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The rapid growth of organometallic chemistry is often attributed to the excitement arising from the discovery of ferrocene and its many analogues.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Ferrocene and its numerous derivatives have no large-scale applications, but have many niche uses that exploit their unusual structure (ligand scaffolds, pharmaceutical candidates), robustness (anti-knock formulations, precursors to materials), and redox reactions (reagents and redox standards).
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Use for global cooling has been proposed.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Ferrocene and its derivatives are antiknock agents added to the petrol used in motor vehicles, and are safer than the now-banned tetraethyllead.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Petrol additive solutions containing ferrocene can be added to unleaded petrol to enable its use in vintage cars designed to run on leaded petrol.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The iron-containing deposits formed from ferrocene can form a conductive coating on the spark plug surfaces.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl, also known as iron carbonyl, is the compound with formula Fe(CO)5.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Under standard conditions Fe(CO)5 is a free-flowing, straw-colored liquid with a pungent odour.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] This compound is a common precursor to diverse iron compounds, including many that are useful in organic synthesis.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is prepared by the reaction of fine iron particles with carbon monoxide.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl is one of the homoleptic metal carbonyls; i.e. metal complexes bonded only to CO ligands.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Other examples include octahedral Cr(CO)6 and tetrahedral Ni(CO)4.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Most metal carbonyls have 18 valence electrons, and Fe(CO)5 fits this pattern with 8 valence electrons on Fe and five pairs of electrons provided by the CO ligands.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Reflecting its symmetrical structure and charge neutrality, Fe(CO)5 is volatile; it is one of the most frequently encountered liquid metal complexes.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Fe(CO)5 adopts a trigonal bipyramidal structure with the Fe atom surrounded by five CO ligands: three in equatorial positions and two axially bound.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is the archetypal fluxional molecule due to the rapid interchange of the axial and equatorial CO groups via the Berry mechanism on the NMR timescale.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Consequently, the13C NMR spectrum exhibits only one signal due to the rapid interchange between nonequivalent CO sites.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In Europe, iron pentacarbonyl was once used as an anti-knock agent in petrol in place of tetraethyllead.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Two more modern alternative fuel additives are ferrocene and methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Fe(CO)5 is used in the production of "carbonyl iron", a finely divided form of iron used in magnetic cores of high-frequency coils for electronics, and for manufacture of the active ingredients of some radar absorbent materials (e.g. iron ball paint).
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] It is famous as a chemical precursor for the synthesis of various iron-based nanoparticles.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Iron pentacarbonyl has been found to be a strong flame speed inhibitor in oxygen based flames.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene is a clear, water-insoluble liquid with a slightly sweet, highly volatile odor reminiscent of paint thinners or other organic solvents.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] It is an aromatic hydrocarbon that is widely used as an industrial feedstock and as a solvent.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Like other solvents, toluene is also used as an inhalant drug for its intoxicating properties.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene and benzene were used as octane rating boosters for aviation fuel by the Royal Air Force in the World War Two.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Tetraethyl lead was manufactured in the USA and was on short supply, so Rolls-Royce engineers built the Rolls-Royce Merlin to work with fuel affed with benzene and toluene.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The Allison V-1710 engine would not run with the RAF fuels as it required tetraethyl lead for lubrication of its valvetrain, but the Packard-built Merlins would.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] This is why the Merlin-engine P-51 Mustangs had a text "Suitable for Aromatics" on their USAAF type description.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene can be used as an octane booster in gasoline fuels used in internal combustion engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene at 86% by volume fueled all the turbo Formula 1 teams in the 1980s, first pioneered by the Honda team.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The remaining 14% was a "filler" of n-heptane, to reduce the octane to meet Formula 1 fuel restrictions.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene also poses similar problems as alcohol fuels, as it eats through standard rubber fuel lines and has no lubricating properties as standard gasoline does, which can break down fuel pumps and cause upper cylinder bore wear.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Toluene has also been used as a coolant for its good heat transfer capabilities in sodium cold traps used in nuclear reactor system loops.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Properties of xylenes and ethylbenzene are nearly identical to toluene, with the latter advertised by a refinery as "component of high performance fuels".
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Isooctane is produced on a massive scale in the petroleum industry, usually as a mixture with related hydrocarbons.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The alkylation process alkylates isobutane with isobutylene using a strong acid catalyst.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In the NExOCTANE process, isobutylene is dimerized into isooctene and then hydrogenated to isooctane.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] In World War II, xylidine was an important antiknock agent in very high performance aviation gasolines.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] Its purpose was to permit high levels of boost pressure in multiple-stage turbochargers, and thus high power at high altitudes, without causing detonation that would destroy the engine.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] The high pressures brought high temperatures of inlet air, making engines prone to knock.
[src:antiknock-agent/anti-knock-agent] This use and storage stabilization methods were important military secrets.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Arenes are typically split into two categories - benzoids, that contain a benzene derivative and follow the benzene ring model, and non-benzoids that contain other aromatic cyclic derivatives.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Aromatic compounds are commonly used in organic synthesis and are involved in many reaction types, following both additions and removals, as well as saturation and dearomatization.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Aromatic compounds are pervasive in nature and industry.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Key industrial aromatic hydrocarbons are benzene, toluene, xylene called BTX.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Many biomolecules have phenyl groups including the so-called aromatic amino acids.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Benzene, C6H6, is the least complex aromatic hydrocarbon, and it was the first one defined as such.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Its bonding nature was first recognized independently by Joseph Loschmidt and August Kekulé in the 19th century.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Each carbon atom in the hexagonal cycle has four electrons to share.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] One electron forms a sigma bond with the hydrogen atom, and one is used in covalently bonding to each of the two neighboring carbons.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] This leaves six electrons, shared equally around the ring in delocalized pi molecular orbitals the size of the ring itself.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] This represents the equivalent nature of the six carbon-carbon bonds all of bond order 1.5.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] This equivalency can also explained by resonance forms.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The electrons are visualized as floating above and below the ring, with the electromagnetic fields they generate acting to keep the ring flat.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The circle symbol for aromaticity was introduced by Sir Robert Robinson and his student James Armit in 1925 and popularized starting in 1959 by the Morrison & Boyd textbook on organic chemistry.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The proper use of the symbol is debated: some publications use it to *any* cyclic π system, while others use it only for those π systems that obey Hückel's rule.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Some argue that, in order to stay in line with Robinson's originally intended proposal, the use of the circle symbol should be limited to monocyclic 6 π-electron systems.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In this way the circle symbol for a six-center six-electron bond can be compared to the Y symbol for a three-center two-electron bond.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Benzene derivatives have from one to six substituents attached to the central benzene core.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Examples of benzene compounds with just one substituent are phenol, which carries a hydroxyl group, and toluene with a methyl group.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] When there is more than one substituent present on the ring, their spatial relationship becomes important for which the arene substitution patterns *ortho*, *meta*, and *para* are devised.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] When reacting to form more complex benzene derivatives, the substituents on a benzene ring can be described as either activated or deactivated, which are electron donating and electron withdrawing respectively.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Activators are known as ortho-para directors, and deactivators are known as meta directors.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Upon reacting, substituents will be added at the ortho, para or meta positions, depending on the directivity of the current substituents to make more complex benzene derivatives, often with several isomers.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Electron flow leading to re-aromatization is key in ensuring the stability of such products.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] For example, three isomers exist for cresol because the methyl group and the hydroxyl group (both ortho para directors) can be placed next to each other (*ortho*), one position removed from each other (*meta*), or two positions removed from each other (*para*).
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Given that both the methyl and hydroxyl group are ortho-para directors, the ortho and para isomers are typically favoured.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Xylenol has two methyl groups in addition to the hydroxyl group, and, for this structure, 6 isomers exist.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Arene rings can stabilize charges, as seen in, for example, phenol (C6H5–OH), which is acidic at the hydroxyl (OH), as charge on the oxygen (alkoxide –O−) is partially delocalized into the benzene ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Although benzylic arenes are common, non-benzylic compounds are also exceedingly important.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Any compound containing a cyclic portion that conforms to Hückel's rule and is not a benzene derivative can be considered a non-benzylic aromatic compound.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Of annulenes larger than benzene, [12]annulene and [14]annulene are weakly aromatic compounds and [18]annulene, Cyclooctadecanonaene, is aromatic, though strain within the structure causes a slight deviation from the precisely planar structure necessary for aromatic categorization.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Another example of a non-benzylic monocyclic arene is the cyclopropenyl (cyclopropenium cation), which satisfies Hückel's rule with an n equal to 0.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Note, only the cationic form of this cyclic propenyl is aromatic, given that neutrality in this compound would violate either the octet rule or Hückel's rule.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Other non-benzylic monocyclic arenes include the aforementioned heteroarenes that can replace carbon atoms with other heteroatoms such as N, O or S.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Common examples of these are the five-membered pyrrole and six-membered pyridine, both of which have a substituted nitrogen.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, also known as polynuclear aromatic compounds (PAHs) are aromatic hydrocarbons that consist of fused aromatic rings and do not contain heteroatoms or carry substituents.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Naphthalene is the simplest example of a PAH.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] PAHs occur in oil, coal, and tar deposits, and are produced as byproducts of fuel burning (whether fossil fuel or biomass).
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] As pollutants, they are of concern because some compounds have been identified as carcinogenic, mutagenic, and teratogenic.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Studies have shown that high levels of PAHs are found, for example, in meat cooked at high temperatures such as grilling or barbecuing, and in smoked fish.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] They are also a good candidate molecule to act as a basis for the earliest forms of life.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In graphene the PAH motif is extended to large 2D sheets.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] A few inorganic silicon ring compounds with similar structure have been synthesized that are also referred to as aromatic.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Aromatic ring systems participate in many organic reactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In aromatic substitution, one substituent on the arene ring, usually hydrogen, is replaced by another reagent.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The two main types are electrophilic aromatic substitution, when the active reagent is an electrophile, and nucleophilic aromatic substitution, when the reagent is a nucleophile.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In radical-nucleophilic aromatic substitution, the active reagent is a radical.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Nucleophilic aromatic substitution involves displacement of a leaving group, such as a halide, on an aromatic ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Aromatic rings usually nucleophilic, but in the presence of electron-withdrawing groups aromatic compounds undergo nucleophilic substitution.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Mechanistically, this reaction differs from a common SN2 reaction, because it occurs at a trigonal carbon atom (sp2 hybridization).
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Hydrogenation of arenes create saturated rings.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The compound 1-naphthol is completely reduced to a mixture of decalin-ol isomers.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In dearomatization reactions the aromaticity of the reactant is lost.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In this regard, the dearomatization is related to hydrogenation.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Arene-arene interactions have attracted much attention.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Pi-stacking (also called **π–π stacking**) refers to the presumptively attractive, noncovalent pi interactions between the pi bonds of aromatic rings, because of orbital overlap.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] According to some authors direct stacking of aromatic rings (the "sandwich interaction") is electrostatically repulsive.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Sandwiched orientations are relatively rare.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Pi stacking is repulsive as it places carbon atoms with partial negative charges from one ring on top of other partial negatively charged carbon atoms from the second ring and hydrogen atoms with partial positive charges on top of other hydrogen atoms that likewise carry partial positive charges.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] In staggered stacking, one of the two aromatic rings is offset sideways so that the carbon atoms with partial negative charge in the first ring are placed above hydrogen atoms with partial positive charge in the second ring so that the electrostatic interactions become attractive.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Likewise, pi-teeing interactions in which the two rings are oriented perpendicular to either other is electrostatically attractive as it places partial positively charged hydrogen atoms in close proximity to partially negatively charged carbon atoms.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] An alternative explanation for the preference for staggered stacking is due to the balance between van der Waals interactions (attractive dispersion plus Pauli repulsion).
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] These staggered stacking and π-teeing interactions between aromatic rings are important in nucleobase stacking within DNA and RNA molecules, protein folding, template-directed synthesis, materials science, and molecular recognition.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Despite the wide use of term pi stacking in the scientific literature, there is no theoretical justification for its use.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The benzene dimer is the prototypical system for the study of pi stacking, and is experimentally bound by 8–12 kJ/mol (2–3 kcal/mol) in the gas phase with a separation of 4.96 Å between the centers of mass for the T-shaped dimer.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] X-ray crystallography reveals perpendicular and offset parallel configurations for many simple aromatic compounds.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Similar offset parallel or perpendicular geometries were observed in a survey of high-resolution x-ray protein crystal structures in the Protein Data Bank.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Analysis of the aromatic amino acids phenylalanine, tyrosine, histidine, and tryptophan indicates that dimers of these side chains have many stabilizing interactions at distances larger than the average van der Waals radii.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The relative binding energies of the three geometries of the benzene dimer can be explained by a balance of quadrupole/quadrupole and London dispersion forces.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] While benzene does not have a dipole moment, it has a strong quadrupole moment.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The local C–H dipole means that there is positive charge on the atoms in the ring and a correspondingly negative charge representing an electron cloud above and below the ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The quadrupole moment is reversed for hexafluorobenzene due to the electronegativity of fluorine.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The benzene dimer in the sandwich configuration is stabilized by London dispersion forces but destabilized by repulsive quadrupole/quadrupole interactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] By offsetting one of the benzene rings, the parallel displaced configuration reduces these repulsive interactions and is stabilized.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The large polarizability of aromatic rings lead to dispersive interactions as major contribution to stacking effects.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] These play a major role for interactions of nucleobases e.g. in DNA.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The T-shaped configuration enjoys favorable quadrupole/quadrupole interactions, as the positive quadrupole of one benzene ring interacts with the negative quadrupole of the other.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The benzene rings are furthest apart in this configuration, so the favorable quadrupole/quadrupole interactions evidently compensate for diminished dispersion forces.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] According to one model, electron-withdrawing substituents lowers the negative quadrupole of the aromatic ring and thereby favor parallel displaced and sandwich conformations.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] By contrast, electron donating groups increase the negative quadrupole, which may stabilize a T-shaped configuration with the proper geometry.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] They used a simple mathematical model based on sigma and pi atomic charges, relative orientations, and van der Waals interactions to qualitatively determine that electrostatics are dominant in substituent effects.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Hunter *et al.* applied a more sophisticated chemical double mutant cycle with a hydrogen-bonded "zipper" to the issue of substituent effects in pi stacking interactions in proteins.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] However, the authors note that direct interactions with the ring substituents, discussed below, also make important contributions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Indeed, the interplay of these two factors may result in the complicated substituent- and geometry-dependent behavior of pi stacking interactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Some experimental and computational evidence suggests that pi stacking interactions are not governed primarily by electrostatic effects.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The relative contributions pi stacking have been borne out by computation.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Trends based on electron donating or withdrawing substituents can be explained by exchange-repulsion and dispersion terms.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] A molecular torsion balance from an aryl ester with two conformational states.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The folded state had a well-defined pi stacking interaction with a T-shaped geometry, whereas the unfolded state had no aryl–aryl interactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The NMR chemical shifts of the two conformations were distinct and could be used to determine the ratio of the two states, which was interpreted as a measure of intramolecular forces.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The authors report that a preference for the folded state is not unique to aryl esters.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] For example, the cyclohexyl ester favored the folded state more so than the phenyl ester, and the tert-butyl ester favored the folded state by a preference greater than that shown by any aryl ester.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] This suggests that aromaticity is not a strict requirement for favorable interaction with an aromatic ring.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Other evidence for non-aromatic pi stacking interactions results include critical studies in theoretical chemistry, explaining the underlying mechanisms of empirical observations.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Grimme reported that the interaction energies of smaller dimers consisting of one or two rings are very similar for both aromatic and saturated compounds.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] This finding is of particular relevance to biology, and suggests that the contribution of pi systems to phenomena such as stacked nucleobases may be overestimated.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] However, it was shown that an increased stabilizing interaction is seen for large aromatic dimers.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] As previously noted, this interaction energy is highly dependent on geometry.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Indeed, large aromatic dimers are only stabilized relative to their saturated counterparts in a sandwich geometry, while their energies are similar in a T-shaped interaction.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] A more direct approach to modeling the role of aromaticity was taken by Bloom and Wheeler.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The authors compared the interactions between benzene and either 2-methylnaphthalene or its non-aromatic isomer, 2-methylene-2,3-dihydronaphthalene.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The latter compound provides a means of conserving the number of p-electrons while, however, removing the effects of delocalization.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Surprisingly, the interaction energies with benzene are higher for the non-aromatic compound, suggesting that pi-bond localization is favorable in pi stacking interactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] The authors also considered a homodesmotic dissection of benzene into ethylene and 1,3-butadiene and compared these interactions in a sandwich with benzene.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Their calculation indicates that the interaction energy between benzene and homodesmotic benzene is higher than that of a benzene dimer in both sandwich and parallel displaced conformations, again highlighting the favorability of localized pi-bond interactions.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] These results strongly suggest that aromaticity is not required for pi stacking interactions in this model.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] Even in light of this evidence, Grimme concludes that pi stacking does indeed exist.
[src:antiknock-agent/aromatic-hydrocarbon] However, he cautions that smaller rings, particularly those in T-shaped conformations, do not behave significantly differently from their saturated counterparts, and that the term should be specified for larger rings in stacked conformations which do seem to exhibit a cooperative pi electron effect.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Kerosene-based jet fuel is formulated to suit the requirements of turbine engines which have no octane requirement and operate over a much wider flight envelope than piston engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Kerosene is also used by most diesel piston engines developed for aviation use, such as those by SMA Engines, Austro Engine, and Thielert.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The main petroleum component used in blending avgas is alkylate, which is a mixture of various isooctanes.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] All grades of avgas that meet CAN 2–3, 25-M82 have a density of 6.01 pounds per US gallon (720 g/L) at 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] (6 lb/U.S. gal is commonly used in America for weight and balance computation.) Density increases to 6.41 pounds per US gallon (768 g/L) at −40 °C (−40 °F), and decreases by about 0.1% per 1 °C (1.8 °F) increase in temperature.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Avgas has an emission coefficient (or factor) of 18.355 pounds per US gallon (2.1994 kg/L) of CO2 or about 3.07 units of weight CO2 produced per unit weight of fuel used.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Avgas is less volatile, with a Reid vapor pressure range of 5.5 to 7 psi, than automotive gasoline, with a range of 8 to 14 psi.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] A minimum limit ensures adequate volatility for engine starting.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The upper limits are related to atmospheric pressure at sea level, 14.7 psi, for motor vehicles and ambient pressure at 22,000 ft, 6.25 psi, for aircraft.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The lower avgas volatility reduces the chance of vapor lock in fuel lines at altitudes up to 22,000 ft.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The high octane ratings were traditionally achieved by the addition of tetraethyllead, a highly toxic substance that was phased out of automotive use in most countries in the late 20th century.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Historically, many post-WWII developed, low-powered 4- and 6-cylinder piston aircraft engines were designed to use leaded fuels; an unleaded replacement fuel is being developed and certified for these engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Some reciprocating-engine aircraft still require leaded fuels, but some do not, and some can burn unleaded gasoline if a special oil additive is used.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The annual US usage of avgas was 186 million US gallons (700,000 m3) in 2008, and was approximately 0.14% of the motor gasoline consumption.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] From 1983 through 2008, US usage of avgas declined consistently by approximately 7.5 million US gallons (28,000 m3) each year.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] As of 2024, the annual US usage of avgas was 180 million US gallons (680,000 m3), most of which contained lead, and 170,000 aircraft in the US used leaded avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In Europe, avgas remains the most common piston-engine fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] High prices have encouraged efforts to convert to diesel engines burning jet fuel, which is more readily available, less expensive, and has advantages for aviation use.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Grades of avgas are identified by two numbers associated with its Motor Octane Number (MON).
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The first number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to "aviation lean" standards, which is similar to the anti-knock index or "pump rating" given to automotive gasoline in the US.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The second number indicates the octane rating of the fuel tested to the "aviation rich" standard, which tries to simulate a supercharged condition with a rich mixture, elevated temperatures, and a high manifold pressure.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] For example, **100/130** avgas has an octane rating of 100 at the lean settings usually used for cruising and 130 at the rich settings used for take-off and other full-power conditions.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Antiknock agents such as tetraethyl lead (TEL) help to control detonation and provide lubrication.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] One gram of TEL contains 640.6 milligrams of lead.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] 100LL (pronounced "one hundred low lead") may contain a maximum of one-half the tetraethyllead allowed in 100/130 (green) avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Some of the lower-powered (100–150 horsepower or 75–112 kilowatts) aviation engines that were developed in the late 1990s are designed to run on unleaded fuel and on 100LL, an example being the Rotax 912.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Automotive gasoline—known as mogas or autogas among aviators—that does not contain ethanol may be used in certified aircraft that have a Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) for automotive gasoline, as well as in experimental aircraft and ultralight aircraft.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Some oxygenates other than ethanol are approved, but these STC's prohibit ethanol-laced gasolines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Ethanol-treated gasoline is susceptible to phase-separation which is very possible due to the altitude/temperature changes light airplanes undergo in ordinary flight.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This ethanol-treated fuel can flood the fuel system with water which can cause in-flight engine failure.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Additionally, the phase-separated fuel can leave remaining portions that do not meet octane requirements due to the loss of the ethanol in the water-absorption process.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Further, the ethanol can attack materials in aircraft construction which pre-date "gasohol" fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Most of these applicable aircraft have low-compression engines which were originally certified to run on 80/87 avgas and require only "regular" 87 anti-knock index automotive gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Examples include the popular Cessna 172 Skyhawk or Piper Cherokee with the 150 hp (110 kW) variant of the Lycoming O-320.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Some aircraft engines were originally certified using a 91/96 avgas and have STC's available to run "premium" 91 anti-knock index (AKI) automotive gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Examples include some Cherokees with the 160 hp (120 kW) Lycoming O-320 or 180 hp (130 kW) O-360, or the Cessna 152 with the O-235.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The AKI rating of typical automotive fuel might not directly correspond to the 91/96 avgas used to certify engines, as motor vehicle pumps in the US use the so-called "(R + M)/2" averaged motor vehicle octane rating system as posted on gas station pumps.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Sensitivity is roughly 8–10 points, meaning that a 91 AKI fuel might have a MON of as low as 86.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The extensive testing process required to obtain an STC for the engine/airframe combination helps ensure that, for those eligible aircraft, 91 AKI fuel provides sufficient detonation margin under normal conditions.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Automotive gasoline is not a fully viable replacement for avgas in many aircraft, because many high-performance and/or turbocharged airplane engines have been designed to use 100 octane fuel and modifications are necessary in order to use lower-octane fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Many general aviation aircraft engines were designed to run on 80/87 octane, roughly the standard (as unleaded fuel only, with the "{R+M}/2" 87 octane rating) for North American automobiles today.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Direct conversions to run on automotive fuel are fairly common, by supplemental type certificate (STC).
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] However, the alloys used in aviation engine construction are chosen for their durability and synergistic relationship with the protective features of lead, and engine wear in the valves is a potential problem on automotive gasoline conversions.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Fortunately, significant history of engines converted to mogas has shown that very few engine problems are caused by automotive gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] A larger problem stems from the higher and wider range of allowable vapor pressures found in automotive gasoline; this can pose some risk to aviation users if fuel system design considerations are not taken into account.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Automotive gasoline can vaporize in fuel lines, causing a vapor lock (a bubble in the line) or fuel pump cavitation, thereby starving the engine of fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This does not constitute an insurmountable obstacle, but merely requires examination of the fuel system, ensuring adequate shielding from high temperatures and maintaining sufficient pressure in the fuel lines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This is the main reason why both the specific engine model as well as the aircraft in which it is installed must be supplementally certified for the conversion.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] A good example of this is the Piper Cherokee with high-compression 160 or 180 hp (120 or 130 kW) engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Only later versions of the airframe with different engine cowling and exhaust arrangements are applicable for the automotive fuel STC, and even then require fuel-system modifications.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Vapor lock typically occurs in fuel systems where a mechanically-driven fuel pump mounted on the engine draws fuel from a tank mounted lower than the pump.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The reduced pressure in the line can cause the more volatile components in automotive gasoline to flash into vapor, forming bubbles in the fuel line and interrupting fuel flow.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] If an electric boost pump is mounted in the fuel tank to push fuel toward the engine, as is common practice in fuel-injected automobiles, the fuel pressure in the lines is maintained above ambient pressure, preventing bubble formation.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Likewise, if the fuel tank is mounted above the engine and fuel flows primarily due to gravity, as in a high-wing airplane, vapor lock cannot occur, using either aviation or automotive fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Fuel-injected engines in automobiles also usually have a "fuel return" line to send unused fuel back to the tank, which has the benefit of equalizing the fuel's temperature throughout the system, further reducing the chance of vapor lock developing.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In addition to vapor locking potential, automotive gasoline does not have the same quality tracking as aviation gasoline.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] To help solve this problem, the specification for an aviation fuel known as 82UL was developed as essentially automotive gasoline with additional quality tracking and restrictions on permissible additives.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This fuel is not currently in production and no refiners have committed to producing it.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Rotax allows up to 10% ethanol (similar to E10 fuel for cars) in the fuel for Rotax 912 engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Light sport aircraft that are specified by the manufacturer to tolerate alcohol in the fuel system can use up to 10% ethanol.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Fuel dyes aid ground crew and pilots in identifying and distinguishing the fuel grades and most are specified by ASTM D910 or other standards.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Dyes for the fuel are required in some countries.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The 100LL phase-out has been called "one of modern GA's most pressing problems", because 70% of 100LL aviation fuel is used by the 30% of the aircraft in the general aviation fleet that cannot use any of the existing alternatives.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The airframe must also be certified to use the fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In February 2008, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced that the company is very concerned about future availability of 100LL, and as a result, they would develop a line of diesel engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In a February 2008 interview, TCM president Rhett Ross indicated belief that the aviation industry will be "forced out" of using 100LL in the near future, leaving automotive fuel and jet fuel as the only alternatives.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In May 2010, TCM announced that they had licensed development of the SMA SR305 diesel engine.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In November 2008, National Air Transportation Association's president Jim Coyne indicated that the environmental impact of aviation is expected to be a big issue over the next few years and will result in the phasing out of 100LL because of its lead content.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] By May 2012, the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA Unleaded Avgas Transition rulemaking committee) had put together a plan in conjunction with industry to replace leaded avgas with an unleaded alternative within 11 years.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Given the progress already made on 100SF and G100UL, the replacement time might be shorter than that 2023 estimate.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Each candidate fuel must meet a checklist of 12 fuel specification parameters and 4 distribution and storage parameters.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The FAA has requested a maximum of US$60M to fund the administration of the changeover.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In July 2014, nine companies and consortiums submitted proposals to the *Piston Aviation Fuels Initiative* (PAFI) to assess fuels without tetraethyl lead.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Phase one testing is performed at the William J.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Hughes Technical Center for a FAA approved industry replacement by 2018.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In July 2021, the first commercially-produced unleaded avgas, GAMI's G100UL, was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration through a Supplemental Type Certificate.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Lycoming Engines provides a list of engines and fuels that are compatible with unleaded fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Prior to 2022, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) indicated that leaded avgas is required in their engines, and not unleaded auto fuels: "Current aircraft engines feature valve gear components which are designed for compatibility with the leaded ASTM D910 fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In such fuels, the lead acts as a lubricant, coating the contact areas between the valve, guide, and seat.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] They have announced a formal application to the FAA to approve the use of UL91 and UL94 in selected engines, stating that "Continental considers 91UL and 94UL fuel as a transitional step in a long-term strategy to reach a more sustainable aviation".
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Hjelmco Oil first introduced unleaded Avgas grades in Europe in 2003, after its success with 80UL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This grade of Avgas is manufactured to meet ASTM D7547.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Many common Lycoming engines are certified to run on this particular grade of Avgas, and Cessna has approved the use of this fuel in a large number of their piston fleet.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This fuel is also usable in any aircraft in Europe or the United Kingdom where the engine is certified to use it, whether or not the airframe is certified to do so, too.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The firm Airworthy AutoGas tested an ethanol-free 93 anti-knock index (AKI) premium auto gas on a Lycoming O-360-A4M in 2013.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The fuel is certified under Lycoming Service Instruction 1070 and ASTM D4814.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Unleaded 94 Motor octane fuel (*UL94*) is essentially 100LL without the lead.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In March 2009, Teledyne Continental Motors (TCM) announced they had tested a 94UL fuel that might be the best replacement for 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This 94UL meets the avgas specification including vapor pressure but has not been completely tested for detonation qualities in all Continental engines or under all conditions.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Flight testing has been conducted in an IO-550-B powering a Beechcraft Bonanza and ground testing in Continental O-200, 240, O-470, and O-520 engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In May 2010, TCM indicated that despite industry skepticism, they are proceeding with 94UL and that certification was expected in mid-2013.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In June 2010, Lycoming Engines indicated their opposition to 94UL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Company general manager Michael Kraft stated that aircraft owners do not realize how much performance would be lost with 94UL and characterized the decision to pursue 94UL as a mistake that could cost the aviation industry billions in lost business.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Lycoming believes the industry should be pursuing 100UL instead.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The Lycoming position is supported by aircraft type clubs representing owners of aircraft that would be unable to run on lower octane fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In June 2010, clubs such as the American Bonanza Society, the Malibu Mirage Owners and Pilots Association, and the Cirrus Owners and Pilots Association collectively formed the *Clean 100 Octane Coalition* to represent them on this issue and push for unleaded 100 octane avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In November 2015, UL94 was added as a secondary grade of unleaded aviation gasoline to ASTM D7547, which is the specification that governs UL91 unleaded avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] UL94 meets all of the same specification property limits as 100LL with the exception of a lower motor octane number (94.0 minimum for UL94 vs.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] 99.6 minimum for 100LL) and a decreased maximum lead content.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] UL94 is an unleaded fuel, but as with all ASTM International unleaded gasoline specifications, a *de minimis* amount of unintentionally added lead is permitted.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Since May 2016, UL94, now a product of Swift Fuels, is available for sale at dozens of airports in the United States.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Swift Fuels has an agreement for distribution in Europe.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] UL94 is not intended to be a full replacement for 100LL, but rather is designed to be a drop-in replacement for aircraft with lower-octane-rated engines, such as those that are approved for operation on Grade 80 avgas (or lower), UL91, or mogas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] It is estimated that up to 65% of the fleet of current general aviation piston-engine-powered aircraft can operate on UL94 with no modifications to either the engine or airframe.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Some aircraft, however, do require a FAA-approved Supplemental Type Certificate (STC) to be purchased to allow for operation on UL94.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] UL94 has a minimum Motor octane number (MON, which is the octane rating employed for grading aviation gasoline) of 94.0.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] AKI is the octane rating used to grade all U.S. automotive gasoline (typical values at the pump can include 87, 89, 91, and 93), and also the 93UL fuel from Airworthy AutoGas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The minimum AKI of UL94, as sold by Swift Fuels, is 98.0.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The publication of the SAIB, especially the August 2016 revision, eliminated the need for many of the UL94 STCs being sold by Swift Fuels, as the majority of the aircraft on the STC's Approved Model List are type-certified to use 80-octane or lower avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] On April 6, 2017, Lycoming Engines published Service Instruction 1070V, which adds UL94 as an approved grade of fuel for dozens of engine models, 60% of which are carbureted engines.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Engines with displacements of 235, 320, 360, and 540 cubic inches make up almost 90% of the models approved for UL94.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Swift Fuels, LLC, has attained approval to produce fuel for testing at its pilot plant in Indiana.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Composed of approximately 85% mesitylene and 15% isopentane, the fuel is reportedly scheduled for extensive testing by the FAA to receive certification under the new ASTM D7719 guideline for unleaded 100LL replacement fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The company eventually intends to produce the fuel from renewable biomass feedstocks, and aims to produce something competitive in price with 100LL and currently available alternative fuels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Swift Fuels has suggested that the fuel, formerly referred to as 100SF, will be available for "high performance piston-powered aircraft" before 2020.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] John and Mary-Louise Rusek founded Swift Enterprises in 2001 to develop renewable fuels and hydrogen fuel cells.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] They began testing "Swift 142" in 2006 and patented several alternatives for non-alcohol based fuels which can be derived from biomass fermentation.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Over the next several years, the company sought to build a pilot plant to produce enough fuel for larger-scale testing and submitted fuel to the FAA for testing.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In 2008, an article by technology writer and aviation enthusiast Robert X.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Cringely attracted popular attention to the fuel, as also did a cross-country Swift-Fueled flight by the AOPA's Dave Hirschman.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Swift Enterprises' claims that the fuel could eventually be manufactured much more cheaply than 100LL have been debated in the aviation press.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The FAA found Swift Fuel to have a motor octane number of 104.4, 96.3% of the energy per unit of mass, and 113% of the energy per unit of volume as 100LL, and to meet most of the ASTM D910 standard for leaded aviation fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Following tests in two Lycoming engines, the FAA concluded it performs better than 100LL in detonation testing and will provide a fuel saving of 8% per unit of volume, though it weighs 1 pound per US gallon (120 g/L) more than 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] GC–FID testing showed the fuel to be made primarily of two components — one about 85% by weight and the other about 14% by weight.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Soon afterward, AVweb reported that Continental had begun the process of certifying several of its engines to use the new fuel.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In 2012, Swift Fuels LLC was formed to bring in oil and gas industry experience, scale up production and bring the fuel to market.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] By November 2013, the company had built its pilot plant and received approval to produce fuel in it.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Its most recent patent, approved in 2013, describes methods by which the fuel can be produced from fermentable biomass.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The FAA scheduled UL102 for 2 years of phase 2 testing in its PAFI initiative beginning in the summer of 2016.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In February 2010, General Aviation Modifications Inc.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] (GAMI) announced that it was in the process of developing a 100LL replacement to be called G100UL ("unleaded").
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This fuel is made by blending existing refinery products and yields detonation margins comparable to 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The new fuel is slightly more dense than 100LL, but has a 3.5% higher thermodynamic output.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] G100UL is compatible with 100LL and can be mixed with it in aircraft tanks for use.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In demonstrations held in July 2010, G100UL performed better than 100LL that just meets the minimum specification and performed as well as average production 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] G100UL was approved by the Federal Aviation Administration by the issuance of a Supplemental Type Certificate at AirVenture in July 2021.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The STC was initially only applicable to Lycoming-powered models of the Cessna 172.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The company indicated that the retail cost was expected to be 0.60–0.85 US dollars per US gallon higher than 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This was later revised to 1.00 US dollar per US gallon.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In 2022, Paul Bertorelli of AVweb reported that the FAA was dragging its feet on broadly certifying G100UL, delaying approval of the fuel for more engines and spending over $80 million on EAGLE to re-start a search for an unleaded fuel when G100UL had been under evaluation for over 10 years.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In September 2022, in a surprise announcement, the FAA approved an STC for the use of the fuel for all piston-engined aircraft and engine combinations.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In February 2023, GAMI began selling supplemental type certificates to allow aircraft owners to use the fuel when it becomes available.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In April 2024, GAMI announced that 1 million gallons of G100UL had been produced.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Fuel availability in the US was forecast for airports in California, Washington and Oregon by the middle of 2024 and the rest of the country by 2026.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In December 2024, shortly after G100UL was made available at selected airports in California, several concerns regarding material compatibility arose, as users reported fuel leaks, paint staining, and paint stripping.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In December 2013, Shell Oil announced that they had developed an unleaded 100 octane fuel and will submit it for FAA testing with certification expected within two to three years.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The fuel is alkylate-based with an additive package of aromatics.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] No information has yet been published with regard to its performance, producibility or price.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Industry analysts have indicated that it will likely cost as much as or more than existing 100LL.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In 2018, LyondellBasell and VP Racing Fuels, an established motorsport fuel manufacturer, announced its intention to participate in developing an unleaded fuel for piston-powered aircraft.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] As of December 2024, it has reached Phase 4 of testing, according to the FAA.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] TEL found in leaded avgas and its combustion products are potent neurotoxins that have been shown in scientific research to interfere with brain development in children.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Children in residences or childcare facilities in close proximity to airports with moderate to high piston engine aircraft traffic are at especially high risk of high blood lead levels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] On November 16, 2007, the environmental group Friends of the Earth formally petitioned the EPA, asking them to regulate leaded avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The EPA responded with a notice of petition for rulemaking.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The public comment period on this petition closed on March 17, 2008.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Under a federal court order to set a new standard by October 15, 2008, the EPA cut the acceptable limits for atmospheric lead from the previous standard of 1.5 μg/m3 to 0.15 μg/m3.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] This was the first change to the standard since 1978 and represents an order of magnitude reduction over previous levels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The EPA's own studies have shown that to prevent a measurable decrease in IQ for children deemed most vulnerable, the standard needs to be set much lower, to 0.02 μg/m3.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The EPA identified avgas as one of the most "significant sources of lead".
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] In December 2008, AOPA filed formal comments to the new EPA regulations.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] AOPA has asked the EPA to account for the cost and the safety issues involved with removing lead from avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] They cited that the aviation sector employs more than 1.3 million people in the US and has an economic direct and indirect effect that "exceeds $150 billion annually".
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] AOPA interprets the new regulations as not affecting general aviation as they are currently written.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Publication in the USA Federal Register of an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking by the USA EPA occurred in April 2010.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Despite assertions in the media that leaded avgas will be eliminated in the US by 2017 at the latest date, the EPA confirmed in July 2010 that there is no phase-out date and that setting one would be an FAA responsibility as the EPA has no authority over avgas.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] The FAA administrator stated that regulating lead in avgas is an EPA responsibility, resulting in widespread criticism of both organizations for causing confusion and delaying solutions.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] "There is no reason to believe 100 low-lead will become unavailable in the foreseeable future," Fuller stated.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Final results from EPA's lead modeling study at the Santa Monica Airport shows off-airport levels below current 150 ng/m3 and possible future 20 ng/m3 levels.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Fifteen of 17 airports monitored during a year-long study in the US by the EPA have lead emissions well below the current National Ambient Air Quality Standard (NAAQS) for lead.
[src:antiknock-agent/avgas] Avgas is occasionally used in amateur auto racing cars as its octane rating is higher than automotive gasoline thus allowing the engines to run at higher compression ratios.
